TI: DEVICE POTENTIALS OF PLANAR SUPERLATTICES, QUANTUM WIRES AND QUANTUM BOXES
AB: Novel properties of electrons in laterally-defined (LD) superstructures have been reviewed and their device potentials are discussed, including the possible suppression of both impurity and optical phonon scattering in quantum wires and quantum-box arrays. The importance of fabricating class-1 LD structures, in which most carriers are accomodated in the sharply-defined ground level is emphasized.

AU: HOFMANN, DM; AKIYAMA, M; IKOMA, T
AF: HOFMANN, DM; AKIYAMA, M; IKOMA, T
TI: DEEP LEVELS IN GAAS ON SI GROWN BY MOCVD
AB: Deep levels in GaAs on Si grown by MOCVD in a two step growth sequence (400-degrees-C, 650-degrees-C growth temperature) have been studied by capacitance transient methods. Traps with similar properties as in the homoepitaxial grown As-rich GaAs on GaAs are observed. Rapid thermal annealing shows an increase of the EL2 trap in the temperature range from 500-degrees-C to 800-degrees-C. For higher annealing temperatures EL2 decreases and a trap located at 0.47 eV below the conduction band increases. The unusual incrase of EL2 is explained by changes in the dislocation formation, while the high temperature annealing behavior of the traps is due to As and Si outdiffusion.

AU: ZHAO, XW; HIRAKAWA, K; IKOMA, T
AF: ZHAO, XW; HIRAKAWA, K; IKOMA, T
TI: DIFFUSION AND PHOTOLUMINESCENCE OF ERBIUM IN GAAS AND INP
AB: The rare earth element, Er, was successfully diffused into GaAs and InP at low temperatures (300-degrees-C - 700-degrees-C) and the diffusivity was determined. The small activation energy (0.30eV) of the diffusivity in GaAs suggests the interstitial-type diffusion dominates. Two intense and three weak sharp Er-related photoluminescence (PL) lines were observed at approximately 1.55-mu-m in both Er-diffused GaAs and InP. The emission energies and the line-widths of Er-related luminescences depend on neither host materials nor temperatures, indicating that these sharp emission lines are due to 4f-intracenter transitions in Er3+ ions. The result indicates that the diffused Er3+ ions substitute the cation site in III-V compound semiconductors.

AU: Nakayama, T; Kubo, RT; Kishimoto, H; Asano, Y; Tada, T
AF: Nakayama, Toshinori; Kubo, Ralph T.; Kishimoto, Hidehiro; Asano, Yoshihiro; Tada, Tomio
TI: Biochemical identification of I-J as a novel dimeric surface molecule on mouse helper and suppressor T cell clones
AB: A monoclonal anti-1-J(k) antibody JK10-23 was capable of precipitating the putative I-J(k) molecule from NP-40 lysates of I-125-surface labelled mouse T cell clones with either helper or suppressor functions. The I-J molecule detected by specific immunoprecipitedion and subsequent one- or two-dimensional gel analysis was a Mr 84-90 K dimer composed of 42-46 K glycopeptide subunits having isoelectric point pH 5.3 to 6.4. A monomeric form of I-J also existed in some of the T cell clones. The I-J subunit was a glycosylated polypeptide with a 41 K backbone having at least two glycosylation sites. I-J was distinguishable from other known dimeric T cell surface molecules with comparable molecular size, that is, T cell receptor 43 heterodimer, A1 and YE molecules expressed on a T cell leukemia EL4, and mouse CD28. The I-J(k) molecule was precipitable from T cell clones with I-A(k) and I-E-k restriction specificities Including a clone derived from an H-2(b) -> H-2(bxk)F(1) radiation bone marrow chimera. None of the H-2(b)-restricted T cell clones from H-2(b) and its F-1 showed the I-J(k) immunoreactivity. T cell clones having either I-A(b) or I-E-k restriction specificities derived from Intra-H-2 recombinant mouse B10.A(5R) were positive for the I-J(k), while an I-A(b)-restricted T cell clone from B10.A(3R) was negative in the I-J(k) immunoprecipitation. The results indicate that I-J is a novel dimeric surface molecule, most likely to be a homodimer, expressed on T cells according to the major histocompatibility complex.
